title: Niggemann wins CWC title, Rosholt capture boys title
text:
Niggemann wins CWC title, Rosholt capture boys title Stevens Point Journal Media 11:17 p.m. CDT October 15, 2015 (Photo: Getty Images/iStockphoto) CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
STEVENS POINT – Amherst’s Alissa Niggemann won a photo finish against Erika Kisting of Iola-Scandinavia to bring home the Central Wisconsin Conference girls championship at Standing Rocks Park on Thursday. 
Niggemann covered the 5,000-meter course in a time of 19 minutes, 2.5 seconds to edge Kisting, who crossed the finish line just three-tenths of a second behind the winner. 
Wittenberg-Birnamwood claimed the girls team championship by placing all five runners in the top 18 overall led by Paige Norrbom, who wound up sixth in 20:41.3, to finish with 61 points. Amherst was second with 83 points. 
Leighten Fischer ran to a fourth-place overall finish in 20:01.3 to help the Thunderbirds finish third with 86 points. 
Rosholt dominated the boys race just missing out on a sweep of the top five runners by one spot. The Hornets wound up with 16 points paced by CWC individual champion Adam Rzentkowski, who crossed the finish line in a time of 16:43.5. 
Pacelli’s Thomas Basala grabbed a runner-up overall finish with a time of 17:08.5, but since the Cardinals didn’t have a complete team, his performance didn’t count in the team results. 
Individuals placing in the top seven earned first team All-conference honors, while runners placing eighth through 14th garnered second team recognition. 
Girls 
Team standings: 1. Wittenberg-Birnamwood 61; 2. Amherst 83; 3. Rosholt 86; 4. Iola-Scandinavia 101; 5. Pacelli 102; 6. Marion 147; 7. Weyauwega-Fremont 156; 8. Bonduel 168; 9. Manawa, Incomplete. 
Wittenberg-Birnamwood (61): 6. Paige Norrbom, 20:41.3; 9. Alexis Baillett, 21:16.8; 13. Emily Norrbom, 21:32; 15. Siri Zeinert, 21:39.7; 18. Erica Wendler, 21:54.4. 
Amherst (83): 1. Alissa Niggemann, 19:02.5; 11. Lindsay Dose, 21:27.2; 20. Anja Werner, 22:00.7; 25. Shayna Cisewski, 22:33.9; 26. Rebecca Ostrowski, 22:34.3. 
Rosholt (86): 5. Brittany Gagas, 20:11.4; 7. Mikaela Glodowski, 20:43.7; 23. Riley Walski, 22:30.3; 24. Taylor Krogwold, 22:31.7; 27. Lexi Cordova, 22:41.5. 
Iola-Scandinavia (101): 2. Erika Kisting, 19:02.8; 4. Leighten Fischer, 20:01.3; 8. Jada Beacom, 21:11.7; 39. Natalie Rustad, 23:37.8; 48. Haley Ullom, 25:31.6. 
Pacelli (102): 14. Christonna Shafranski, 21:39.7; 16. Adrianna Kosobucki, 21:45.2; 17. Grace Van Handel, 21:47.2; 19. Grace Engebretson, 22:00.3; 36. Dominique Jamison, 23:19.9. 
Boys 
Team standings: 1. Rosholt 16; 2. Bonduel 61; 3. Amherst 68; 4. Wittenberg-Birnamwood 100; 5. Manawa 127; 6. Iola-Scandinavia, Marion, Pacelli, Weyauwega-Fremont and Menominee Indian, Incomplete. 
Rosholt (16): 1. Adam Rzentkowski, 16:43.5; 2. Bailey Zdroik, 17:25.6; 3. Sawyer Fleming, 17:54.3; 4. Ryan Hoppa, 17:55.3; 6. Dausen Anderson, 18:08.6. 
Amherst (68): 8. Seth Barnes, 18:25.2; 9. Adam Wise, 18:36.2; 14. Sawyer Eiden, 18:53; 18. Cole McKenzie, 19:07.2; 19. David Rieck, 19:15.4. 
Wittenberg-Birnamwood (100): 13. Hunter Schroepfer, 18:51.4; 15. Damon Wolff, 18:54.6; 23. Teagan Lehman, 19:38.2; 24. Ethan Wesolowski, 19:38.3; 25. Alex Nelson, 19:41.4. 
Iola-Scandinavia (Inc.): 13. Erick Kriewaldt, 18:47.9; 42. Trenton Niemi, 23:36.2. 
Pacelli (Inc.): 2. Thomas Basala, 17:08.5; 17. Trevor Frane, 18:52.2; 44. Curtis Carlson, 23:55.3; 49. Nate Bronk, 33:51.2. 
BOYS SOCCER 
SPASH 2 
D.C. Everest 1 
STEVENS POINT – Jordan Schrieber scored the game-winning goal in the 73rd minute to help the Panthers defeat the Evergreens 2-1 on Thursday night. The Panthers also benefitted from an own goal by D.C. Everest in the 41 st minute. 
Jack Mittlestead scored the Evergreens only goal in the 66th minute, while keeper Alex Pagel had 8 saves in the loss. 
Keeper Matt Altman had 5 saves for the Panthers in the winning effort. 
“Good game, very nice way for SPASH to get a conference win,” said SPASH coach Mark Peel. “It keeps the win streak going and I’m happy with the boys as they keep improving.” 
D.C. Everest
